<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="KR1e0001-en-0b1b451b" type="transl"><teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>Zuo Tradition</title><editor role="translator">Durant et al.</editor></titleStmt><publicationStmt><ab>published electronically as part of the TLS project at https://hxwd.org</ab><availability status="4">The copyright status of this work is unclear</availability></publicationStmt><sourceDesc><bibl><title>Zuo Tradition</title>Seattle: Univ of Washington Press, 2020</bibl><ab>Translation of <bibl corresp="#KR1e0001"><title xml:lang="och">春秋左傳</title></bibl> into <lang xml:lang="en">English</lang>.</ab></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><creation resp="#CH">Initially created: <date>2024-01-12T22:08:25.187+09:00</date> by CH</creation></profileDesc></teiHeader><text><body><div><head>Translated parts</head><p xml:id="KR1e0001-start"><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_006-98a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-27T02:25:16.844+09:00">Since that man has united a grand and brash nature with hardness,79 On this interpretation, see Yang, 2:541.</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_006-98a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:09:17.679+09:00">how could he die a natural death?</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_009-484a.58" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:14:06.521+09:00">Perhaps this refers to how results must come from one’s own integrity.</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_009-484a.59" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:14:16.771+09:00">When good faith comes from one’s own integrity,</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_009-485a.1" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:14:38.166+09:00">then achievements canbe recorded.”</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.76" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:41:02.932+09:00">By command of kings and covenant elders</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.77" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:41:11.423+09:00">theborders were drawn out;</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.78" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:41:18.072+09:00">officers were set up for these borders,</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.79" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:41:28.313+09:00">andthey were marked with signs and flags</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.80" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:41:36.336+09:00"> and noted in statutes andregulations,</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.81" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:41:42.409+09:00">so that transgressors would be punished.</seg><seg corresp="#KR1e0001_tls_010-19a.82" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2024-01-12T22:43:59.183+09:00">But still theborders could not be maintained.42</seg></p></div></body></text></TEI>